gomodel:SYNGO_4090  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: Fig2h: Miniature excitatory postsynaptic currents (mEPSCs) from CA1 hippocampal neurons displayed a significantly lower amplitude in Snx27+/- neurons compared to Snx27+/+ neurons.\nFig2i: LTP induced by high-frequency trains (100 Hz for 1 s) was significantly reduced in Snx27+/- mice compared to controls.\nBoth these results suggest that Snx27+/-might affect both AMPAR- and NMDAR-dependent synaptic events.\nFig 3a: Western blot analysis shows that Snx27+/- mice had lower amounts of GluR1, GluR2, NR1, NR2A and NR2B in both synaptosomal membranes and PSD fractions compared to Snx27+/+ littermates.\nFig 4d-f: Cell surface biotinylation experiments show that overexpression of SNX27 resulted in increased cell surface amounts of GluR1 and NR1 in GluR1-HEK293 and NR1-NR2A-HEK293 cells. Conversely, knockdown of SNX27 resulted in reduced cell surface expression of GluR1 and NR1. This effect was also evident in primary neurons; with a decrease in cell surface expression of GluR1 and NR1 in primary neurons derived from Snx27+/- mice.\nFig 4g-h: Receptor recycling assay shows that overexpression of SNX27 decreased the amount of internalized biotinylated GluR1 in GluR1-HEK293 cells. Consistent with these overexpression experiments, biotin-labelled GluR1 after treatment with SNX27 siRNA showed increased internalized biotinylated GluR1as compared to control siRNA.\nSupplementary Fig 7: SNX27 does not influence endocytosis of GluR1.. Experimental description: Snx27+/+, Snx27+/- and Snx27-/- mice were generated by crossing heterozygotes on C57BL/6 and 129/SV mixed backgrounds to produce F1 hybrid background mice. Cell surface biotinylation experiments were conducted in HEK cells." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2916-7616" ;
        dc:date           "2021-01-18" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_4090" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10090" .

